    "summary": "Ashurnasirpal II (r. 883–859 BC) was one of the most militarily aggressive and culturally significant kings of the Neo-Assyrian Empire — the ruler who established the template of Assyrian imperial expansion through systematic terror and monumental display. His military campaigns reached from Babylonia to the Mediterranean coast, extracting tribute and brutally punishing resistance: his own inscriptions describe flaying enemies alive, impaling them on stakes, and building towers of skulls as deliberate psychological warfare.\n\nHis reign also produced some of antiquity's finest art. Ashurnasirpal built a magnificent new capital at Nimrud (ancient Kalhu) and decorated his Northwest Palace with extraordinary carved limestone reliefs depicting hunting scenes, royal rituals, and military campaigns — now among the treasures of the British Museum. He inaugurated the palace with a feast reportedly attended by 69,574 guests, sustained for ten days — recorded on an inscription that provides fascinating detail about Assyrian royal logistics and display. Ashurnasirpal's campaigns established Assyrian dominance over the northern Tigris-Euphrates region and opened the routes that his successors would use to expand into Syria, Anatolia, and Egypt.",
